latestPosts.caption:
Your sign to just start 😌✨ + some of my top tips working with brands after 3 years of being a content creator 💌

1. Brand alignment is key!! I used to reach out to brands all the time and get constantly rejected until I started elevating my content and aligning myself with the aesthetic + vibe of the brands I wanted to work with. For example, if you want to work with a luxury brand but most of your content features fast fashion, then this isnt aligned. 

It might take a while to get started with luxury brands, but once you build up your feed aesthetic, portfolio, and start working with a couple, others will also see that brand alignment and want to work with you!

2. It’s a LOT of ‘free’ / unpaid work at first. I’m all for charging for your work, but sometimes it’s also worth taking on unpaid work to get your foot in the door with brands, and then going above and beyond so that they’ll want to work with you on a paid basis later! In fashion, there’s a lot of loaning and gifting involved but over time you’ll eventually get paid opportunities too :) 

3. Content quality always comes first — regardless of how many followers you have! Coming from a brand owner myself who runs influencer programs, we want to see content that represents our brand in an aspirational light + have content that we can use on our own channels. 

Aim to create elevated, high quality content whilst also showing your personality, and the partnerships will come your way 😌

Hope this helps and let me know if you guys have any other questions 🥰

Have been getting so many compliments on my skin recently with this routine but it definitely wasn’t always like this! I used to struggle with acne + breakouts all the time so here are some of my top tips alongside the skincare: 

1. Eating an 80/20 wholefoods diet. I know this sounds simple but your skin always reflects what you put into your body! For me I always breakout after eating processed foods/oily foods so I try to avoid them as much as possible.

2. Double cleansing if you’re wearing sunscreen or makeup always!! Whenever I skip double cleansing, I always end up breaking out the next day. 

3. Not wiping your face with your body towel straight out of the shower because it’s full of bacteria! Instead air dry your face or use a clean face towel. This made the BIGGEST difference for me when it came to reducing small bumps on my forehead!

4. Investing in quality > quantity when it comes to skincare. I used to buy a million products all promising different benefits but I can truly feel the difference when it comes to using quality products & simplifying the routine instead.

5. If you struggle with little bumps / fungal acne, try Salicylic acid 1-2x per week — this unclogs your pores which prevents oil build up into acne! 

6. This is occasional, but I get a hydrafacial every few months to unclog pores and get pimples extracted which makes my skin so much less bumpy and smooth for the next 1-2 months. 

PS. Not sponsored but I get so much of my skincare from @yesstyle because they always have discounts on! Feel free to use the code CLOIEY12 for 12% off orders 95aud+ 🫶

Hope this helps and let me know if you have any questionss <3

Pictured: some aesthetic photos from May so far 
Not pictured: one of the most mentally and physically challenging months I’ve ever gone through

After waking up on a random Tuesday in April with intense nausea, migraines and my voice being completely gone (+ a cascade of other things), these past few weeks have definitely put into perspective what truly matters in life.

Last year this time I was stressing out about fashion week outfits, my ig engagement and upcoming work trips. 

But when something happens to your health you realise how insignificant these worries are in the grand scheme of things. 

Aside from the hospital visits & tests, losing my voice was one of the most emotionally challenging & isolating experiences I never thought I’d go through.

I’ve had to say no to countless plans, meetings, and events. 

I’ve lost one of the main ways I express myself in person and in my content. 

I even cried after bumping into a follower in person (which always makes me so happy) because I couldn’t speak properly 🥺

But…this experience has taught me so much about all the blessings I have in my life and has given me so much perspective on what truly matters in life.

Things I’m grateful for:
- To be able to still move my body 
- To have the privilege and freedom to rest 
- To experience the beauty of nature 
- To still have the ability to communicate without words 
- To have learned how to listen to my body more and notice signs of stress 
- To know that being healthy & connecting with others is truly such a blessing
- To realise that I am so loved & I can still show love in many different ways without saying it verbally 

I’m still healing and slowly regaining strength but I’m so lucky that I WILL be better. 

And take this as another reminder to not compare yourself to what you see online!! Social media is not real life so there’s no point comparing yourself to a highlight reel (this post is evidence of that). 

Ok this caption is getting way too long but sending you all so much love 🫶 and pls thank your body for all it does for you!! It’s your home 🏠 💌
